MissionCommands.Message: {{profileName}}, this is Patrick, I will be your Capsule Communicator today. Do you read?
Loud and clear, Patrick!
Excellent! Seems like you didn't get the measles, let's get you to space!
Sounds like a good plan.
Roger. We are all ready over here, and data seems good. Weather is clear, and we are still go for launch at the scheduled time. Please check the mission BRIEFING in the Mission Pad.
Today's flight will be a suborbital flight with splashdown in the Atlantic. USS Lake Champlain are GO at the recovery location.
When ready, please perform the INTERIOR INSPECTION checklist.
Roger, let's get this cockpit ready.
We are still go for launch. You are running on external power. Use timescale to T-41 minutes.
We are ready to perform the Abort Capability test. Ensure the AMMETER is set to NORM.
AMMETER is at NORM.
ARM the SQUIBS.
And set the DC selector to monitor the Isolated Battery (ISO).

We will power the squibs for 5 seconds upon your request. During the test, verify that the AMPS spike, and that the Abort Light illuminates. When ready, press REQUEST ABORT CAPABILITY TEST from the [C]ommunications menu.
Use timescale to about T-20 minutes
Please start the ABBREVIATED INTERIOR CHECK checklist (use RUN)
We are still go for launch. When complete, you can timescale to about T-10 minutes.
We are 10 minutes from launch. We need to switch to Internal Power. Start the FULL INTERNAL POWER checklist (use RUN).
This will prepare the cockpit for full internal power, and the external power supply will be disconnected from the capsule.
We are 5 minutes from launch. Start the FINAL CHECKS checklist (use RUN).
T-60 seconds. We are GO for launch.
T-30 seconds. Get ready for ignition, and good luck with your flight!
Lift-off!
Things are looking good. Follow the ASCENT checklist until insertion.
Tower is gone!
Roger, we see it too. Complete the ASCENT checklist and verify AUTO RETRO JETT switch is off, and that the Retro Fuse is off.
There goes the Launch Vehicle, turnaround started.
Roger. When the turnaround is complete, check if you can see the launch vehicle through the window.
Switch to fly-by-wire and manually center the launch vehicle in the window then manually change attitude so you can track it with the periscope in magnification mode, and track it for 60 seconds.
Manually return to retrograde attitude, and then set the ASCS to AUTO.
Next, we will test the retrograde rockets. Prepare for retro sequence by running the PRE-RETRO checklist.
Retro sequence starting. Ensure the spacecraft is properly configured and prepare for retro fire. When it fires, follow the RETRO checklist to monitor.
Ignition!
Roger, seems like the retros are working. Prepare for jettison by following the RE-ENTRY checklist. We will soon re-enter.
Retro jettison is green!
Roger, we are on our way home!
0.05g detected, entry interface started.
G's building up. Do you read?
This is {{capsuleName}}, do you read?
This is {{capsuleName}}, do you read?
Loud and clear, good to have you back!
The Drogue is out!
Roger! Prepare for the main!
Main is out, and looking good! What a ride!
Great, that sure was some g's. Recovery is ready to pick you up. Congratulations, this is a great achievement!
Sure was. And you will be the next one up.
This is USS Lake Champlain. We have a visual, chopper heading your way. Good job today!
Roger, Lake Champlain. Thank you.
Splash!
Roger, welcome home, hope you won't get sea sick! Great achievement today, we are catching up with the USSR! Your next flight will be an orbital one. This is MCC signing off. [MISSION END]

Title: MISSION 2 - REDSTONE
Description:
The USSR successfully launched a man to space, beating the US right at the finish line. With the exception of what they say is a successful flight, we know little of their journey, and how space influenced their Cosmonaut.

Your flight is still scheduled for the 5th of May, and the objectives remain the same. We need to learn how a human reacts to being in space, if the Mercury Capsule operates as designed in zero gravity, and your ability to withstand the high g-forces involved.
BriefingText:
Main Objectives:
- Determine man's capabilities in a space environment, and in those environments to which he will be subject upon going into and returning from space.
- Vehicle control during insertion
- Behavior of space systems
- Evaluation of pilot's capabilities in space
- In-flight monitoring
- Retrofire and reentry maneuvers
- Landing and recovery

Scheduled launch time:
May 5, 1961, 14:34:13 UTC

Mission duration:
15 minutes

Launch Vehicle:
Mercury Redstone

Mission Details:
You will enter the cabin at T-90 minutes. The electrical systems have been set up but you will need to follow the COMPLETE CABIN INSPECTION checklist upon ingress, followed by the ABBREVIATED INTERIOR CHECK, FULL INTERNAL POWER, and the FINAL CHECKS checklists before ignition.

The ascent is fully automatic and your primary role will be to monitor systems and verify that systems are nominal. For the duration of the mission you will need to do a systems check ever 30 seconds (see bottom of this briefing). Cabin pressure should bleed and stabilize at 5.5 PSIA during ascent.

Upon insertion and MECO, the tower will jettison and the capsule will perform a full 180 degree turnaround. After verifying that the turnaround has successfully completed and you have a visual of the launch vehicle in the window, you will need to:
A) Check the periscope and report visibility
B) Test the capsule's attitude control system
C) Test the retrorockets and the retro sequence system

The capsule will shortly after reenter the atmosphere and the automatic landing system will deploy the drogue chute, the main chute, and the landing bag for a safe landing. Be prepared for manual override during any of the mission phases.


Systems check:
- Use the selector to check the VOLTS and AMPS of the Main DC Bus, Battery 1, 2, 3, Standby Battery 1, 2, and the Isolated Battery.
- Verify Oxygen Levels on Primary and Secondary Oxygen tanks
- Verify Automatic and Manual Fuel Levels
- G-forces
- Altitude
- Cabin Pressure
